      <div class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert mt-12 max-w-none space-y-6">
        <section>
          <p>
            Hi! I'm Yuval. I'm an applied researcher and engineering leader who is passionate about building things that actually work for real people. I'm motivated by difficult and ambiguous problem spaces and by generating impact. These days I'm deep into AI—working with agentic frameworks, RAG pipelines, and evaluation techniques. I'm exploring what becomes possible when you combine good engineering with thoughtful product thinking and a real understanding of how humans interact with technology.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p>
            My background is in Computer Science and Psychology from Hebrew University, which shapes how I think about building things. I believe great technology should create measurable impact while keeping people at the center—systems need to work for both the machine and the humans using them.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p>
            I spent five years at Mobileye where I founded and led an innovation team exploring new product opportunities. We built patent-pending technologies that shipped to Porsche, Ford, and VW—things like ParallaxNet, a neural network for 3D scene reconstruction that improved accuracy by 52% while running 2× faster, and a method for detecting tire slip with 1 mrad precision. These projects generated over $30M in new business value and taught me how to take ambiguous ideas and turn them into production systems at scale.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <p>
            I've also worked on things outside the corporate world. During the October 2023 crisis, I led a team of engineers building tools for identifying missing persons under serious time pressure. I recently collaborated with a stealth startup in construction tech on an optimization problem that became core to their MVP. I'm someone who uses impact assessment to prioritize what I work on, and I've volunteered with organizations focused on high-leverage problem-solving.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
